    <summary>The email exchanges between Bitcoin developers revolve around the topic of block size increase requirements. Gavin Andresen suggests punishing miners who create slow-to-propagate big blocks by refusing to build on them until they are fully validated. He estimates that if a 20MB block is propagated, it would take at best six seconds to verify it with the current configuration, resulting in a one percent orphan rate increase. Additionally, he notes that their orphan rate is about 0.5% over the past few months but could be above 2% if the network flooded 20MB blocks. Moreover, he suggests accepting 5MB blocks at most, but it is unclear whether he is concerned about the cost or the practicality of handling larger blocks.Furthermore, Alex Mizrahi states that there are many variables in the equation for miners and that the miner is incentivized to invest in their network infrastructure. The discussion is in response to Chun mentioning that his pool is on a slow network, and thus bigger blocks give it a disadvantage. Orphan rate, which is proportional to block size, also plays a role. Alex originally said that those who make big blocks have a disadvantage, but now acknowledges that a disadvantage does exist for those on a slow network.The conversation revolves around the issue of Bitcoin's block size limit and its impact on miners, particularly those in China. The orphan rate increase resulting from producing 20MB blocks will go to whoever is producing them, not the individual miners. However, this all depends on how the miners are connected, and if a miner is on a slow network, they may have a slight disadvantage. Mining profitability involves many equations such as the cost of power, internet cost and connectivity, cost of capital, access to technology other miners don't have, inexpensive labor or rent, inexpensive cooling, ability to use waste heat. The complexity of the mining process and how various factors can impact a miner's success is highlighted. The